To understand the hydrophobicity variation, the FT-IR and the XPS measurements were further taken. Most of the functional groups are removed after the 1000 °C carbonization (Fig. 9
                     a). All the ECNFs show similar characteristics consisting of approximately 84% carbon, approximately 13% nitrogen, and approximately 3% oxygen, where the nitrogen is mainly from the PAN matrix (Fig. 9b and Table 2
                     ). Hydrophobicity strongly depends on the surface property and roughness of the materials [57–60]. The carbon nanofibers prepared with different CGQD contents show a smooth surface (Fig. 4a3-4f3) and have a similar chemical composition. The hydrophobicity improvement of the ECNFs in our work therefore can be ascribed to the increase in diameter of the carbon nanofibers with the increase in CGQD content. In addition, the carbonization temperature also plays an important role in the surface property and the hydrophobicity of the ECNFs. We found that 1000 °C was a suitable carbonization temperature. The details are given in the Supporting Information.
